arguing that discourses of spontaneity—specifically those surrounding the improvvisatrice, or female poetic improviser—were paradoxically used to carve out a new authority for opera composers just as improvisation itself was falling into decline. With this novel and nuanced book, Esse persuasively reclaims the agency of performers and their crucial role in constituting Italian opera as a genre in the nineteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aOperaxGreek influences. 0aOperazItalyy19th century. 0aVocal improvisation (Music)zItalyxPhilosophyxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen singerszFrance. 0aWomen singerszItaly. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  asappho, opera, creativity, femininity, gender, improvisation, performance, performing arts, 19th century, italy, virtuosi, music, theater, stage, salon, poet, poetry, lesbian, sexuality, classics, spontaneity, composers, improvvisatrice, agency, women singers, nonfiction, history, philosophy, musicology, rossini, bellini, pauline viardot, orpheus, collaboration, ensemble, il viaggio a reims, norma, incantation, melody, authority, muse, ancient greece, literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishz978311075412408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021z9783110753899oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226741802423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226741802/original  a978-3